Although the state-run referral facility, the Department of Maternal and Child Health (DMCH), provides no-cost abortion, the lack of information available about receiving care and the limited number of DMCH clinics in Kyrgyzstan mean most women receive information on abortion from their community or their healthcare providers. As of 2013, there were 23 publicly-funded DMCH-supported abortion and contraceptive services in Kyrgyzstan, but only six DMCH sites provide abortion services. Nevertheless, due to cultural and religious beliefs, societal pressure and health system inequities, approximately 20% of all pregnancies end in abortion.

In remote rural areas of Kyrgyzstan, the majority of women (especially those living in poverty) choose to terminate a pregnancy first-trimester using unregistered abortion medication. Black-market abortion medication is easily accessible, though it commonly causes health complications. To better understand the complications sterilization and first trimester abortion medication services posed to poor and rural women of Kyrgyzstan, this innovative qualitative study, conducted in 2014, aimed to develop a better understanding of women’s experiences using black-market abortion medication procured online.
